<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by own:
[I]One of my favorite CRPG's of all time would have to be Baldurs Gate 1.  The reason is because Before BG1, the last two RPG's I really actually played were Daggerfall and Betrayal in Antara.  I loved both those two games, though I never actually beat Daggerfall...

Anyway, I got busier after that and didn't have much time to play games, especially RPG's.  I finally freed up some time a few months before BG1 was released.  I saw the game, got the trailor for it, looked at all the screen shots and read all the info... ahhh everything about it made me want it bad!  Finally December 24th came around and me and my friend both drove down to the store and bought a copy(that we already had on reserve of course).  He went to his place while I went back to my place.  Then we connected to eachother over the phone, direct modem to modem play before we event tried single player(exact same thing anyway).  The first thing I did was attack the bartender for being a smart ellic, the wizard across the room killed me and we disconnected from eachother hehe.  He called me up and we had a laugh about it, then we talked about strategy and to SAVE the game right away so that didn't happen again ;)

Finally we got going, and we played for 14 hours straight!  In our first session we made it to that one bandit camp with the guy with the armor, can't remember exactly what it all was been 5 years now.  It was pretty fun, we would create "bate" characters to run ahead and distract the tough monsters/villains while we used bows from afar.  We ended up beating the game in 3 or 4 days over the modem2modem feature.  After that... we BEAT IT AGAIN playing out the game differant ways.  I remember how pissed he was when I started killing innocents one time and he became a "fallen ranger" ahaha.  So BG1 is one of my best CRPG experiences ever.  After that I became busy again and haven't had the time to play CRPG's much.  I played BG2, and IWD of course, great games, but the experience wasn't quite the same.  NWN was good a few times when you played with people you actually knew, but would rather just play the real AD&D.

As for console RPG's, my 2 favorite are Legends of Zelda: Link to the Past (SNES) and Secret of Mana (SNES).

I am going to have to go and buy Planescape: Torment after reading what all you guys said about it, and of course Divine Divinity.[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
